blocks.text: WORLD'S FAIR, NEW YORK – A strenuous 24 hours trip. We drove to New York from Lancaster, leaving home at 4:00 A. M. and returning at the same time the following morning. Sam and Marion Rohrer, Bill and Ve Huber, Gordon and Kitty. Trip made in Gordon's car. July 18, 1940. This was the second year of the Fair.

blocks.text: Week-end Trip to the Mountains of Virginia and West Virginia with Bill and Ve Huber. Fall, 1942. From Lancaster to Fred- erick, Md; crossed Potomac at Point of Rocks; to Front Royal; over Skyline Drive to Waynesboro, Va; night near Staunton; visited Natural Chimneys; climbed Reddish Knob; then up thr- ough mountains of West Virginia to Elkins; and home via Cum- berland, Md.

Above – on the road between Harrisonburg, Va. and Franklin, W. Va. This point at the crest of the mountain is the dividing line between Virginia and West Virginia. Elevation 3,450 ft. There are excellent mountain views in both directionss.

Above — bridges were sometimes dis-
pensed with on the mountain roads
of West Virginia. Entering George
Washington National Forest.
Above - views from the fire tower on Reddish Knob, W. Va. Elevation is 4,398 feet. A good gravel road, through forests, leads to the tower.

blocks.text: Nancy, Kathy, Cindy -
Kathy and Cindy, showing drifts even after a week of sunshine.
Kathy , Cindy , Nancy .
The heaviest snows of the winter came in February. Drifts after repeated snows in many places were higher than an automobile. Traffic was everywhere impaired and schools were closed for several days.
